## Netflix Data Analysis — Business Requirements Document

## 1. Project Overview
This project aims to analyze publicly available Netflix content data to gain insights into trends in movies and TV shows. It will help understand content distribution, popular genres, release trends, and production countries.

## 2. Business Objectives
Identify the distribution of content types (Movies vs TV Shows) on Netflix.
Understand how Netflix’s content releases have changed over time (yearly trends).
Determine the most popular genres featured on Netflix.
Identify key production countries contributing content.
Provide actionable insights for data enthusiasts or stakeholders interested in entertainment trends.

## 3. Scope
Included:
Analysis of Netflix dataset containing content metadata.
Data exploration, cleaning, and visualization using Python libraries (Pandas, Matplotlib, Seaborn).
Presentation of insights through charts and summaries.
Excluded:
Analysis of user viewing behavior or ratings.
Machine learning recommendations (planned as future work).
Any proprietary or non-public Netflix data.

## 4. Stakeholders
Data Science learners and enthusiasts.
Netflix content analysts (hypothetical).
General public interested in media trends.

#  5. Data Requirements
Use the netflix_titles.csv dataset containing content details such as title, type, release year, genre, country, etc.
Handle missing or inconsistent data appropriately.

## 6. Functional Requirements
Import and clean dataset.
Explore content type distribution (Movies vs TV Shows).
Analyze yearly release trends.
Identify top genres and production countries.
Visualize all findings with clear, informative graphs.

## 7. Non-Functional Requirements
Project should be beginner-friendly and well documented.
Code must be readable and commented.
Visualizations should be clear and professional.
Repository structure should be organized and easy to navigate.

## 8. Deliverables
Cleaned dataset (stored in data/).
Jupyter Notebook with analysis (notebooks/netflix_analysis.ipynb).
Visualizations saved as images (images/).
README with project overview and insights.
Additional documentation explaining code and project background.
